info.title: What-If API
info.description: The What-If API supports the analysis of the impact of traffic restrictions (a given area closed to the traffic from a given date and time to a given date and time) on the public transport. It also supports the browsing across the network of the public transport, the displaying of timetables, and other.

post.summary: For assessing the impact of a closure scenario on the public transport.

fromDateTime.description: ISO 8601 datetime that indicates when the restriction begins

toDateTime.description: ISO 8601 datetime that indicates when the restriction terminates

closedZones.description: WKT representation of the closed zone(s)

200.description: Statistics (KPI) and full details about the impact of the scenario on the public transport.

metrics.description: Some statistics (KPI) about the impact of the scenario

routes.description: The number of the affected routes

traps.description: The number of the traps (the count of the trips such that the bus is expected to enter the closed area before of the closure, but it is not expected to leave it in time, based on the timetable of the trip).

ndr_trips.description: The number of the trips that are affected despite not having any stop in the closed area, just because they would have traversed the closed area if it had not been closed.

trips.description: The total number of the affected trips

agencies.description: The number of the affected agencies

stops.description: The number of the affected stops (intended as the number of not to be confused with the bus stops)

details.description: Full details about the impact of the scenario

post.summary: For browsing across the network of the public transport.

list.description: Set this to "graphs" and also set the "stop" parameter, to get a list (JSON array of strings) of the agencies (tipically one) that use the stop (each agency being identified through the URI of its corresponding graph in KB). Set this to "timetable" and also set the "agency", "stop" and possibly "limit" parameters, to get the timetable of the stop. Set this to "stops" and also set the "agency" and "trip" parameters, to get the list (JSON array of objects, each including the name, the code, the time of arrival and departure) of the stops of the trip. Set this to "trips" and also set the "agency", "route", "stop",  "date", and possibly "crosstrip" parameters, to get the list of the trips that run on the given route in the given date and that stop at the given bus stop (and that appear in the list of the crosstrips, if any). Set this to "routes" and also set the "agency" and "stop" parameters, to get the list of the routes of which the given stop is part. Instead, set this to "routes" with "agency", "date", and a set of "crosstrip" parameters, to get the list of the routes that run one at least of the given trips in the given date. Omit this, and set the "stop", "fromDateTime" and "toDateTime" parameters instead, to get full details about the trips that are planned to stop at the given bus stop in the specified period.

stop.description: The URI of the stop of your interest

agency.description: The URI of the agency of your interest

trip.description: The URI of the trip of your interest

route.description: The URI of the route of your interest

fromDateTime.description: The date and time when the period of interest begins

toDateTime.description: The date and time when the period of interest terminates

crosstrip.description: The URI of a trip. A number of crosstrip parameters is tipically set per request. They are used for filtering lists of routes (give me back only those routes that run one at least of these trips), or of trips (give me back a trip only if it is one of these trips).

limit.description: How many entries to display in the timetable

200.description: The content and format of the response depends on the _list_ parameter.
